This pistol is a 1911 chambered in .45 ACP with a 5 inch barrel. The Spartan edition has an "oil rubbed bronze" nitron finish and 24k gold inlay, which is tough as nails and looks absolutely amazing in person. Depending on the lighting, this finish appears several different colors. The writing on the grips and slide reads "Molon Labe" in ancient greek, which means "Come and take them". This is what King Leonides told the invading armies when told to lay down their arms, and is a motto of patriotism and the 2nd amendment.


The pistol comes fully upgraded with match barrel, checkered front strap and main spring housing, magwell for faster reloading, skeletonized trigger and commander-style hammer, very bright trijicon night sights, lowered/flared ejection port, beavertail with memory bump, and much more. The slide to frame and barrel to bushing fit is absolutely perfect with no play, and the slide action is smooth as glass. The trigger is adjustable, and breaks clean and crisp. This gun is as accurate as they get, and is an absolute pleasure to shoot. This  gun has exactly 150 flawless rounds through it and is in perfect condition, not even broken in. 

The pistol comes with two stainless steel magazines, the original box and paperwork, a sig sauer bumper sticker, and for the right price I will include a sig paddle style retention holster and a custom made leather/carbon fiber kydex hybrid holster for in the waistband concealed carry (see pics). 

I am NOT interested in any trades of any kind. Buyer must have valid TN driver's license and be able to legally own a handgun. Handgun carry permit holders preferred. Must be willing to meet locally face to face and fill out a bill of sale for both of our records. 

Please feel free to email me with any questions! Thanks for looking!!

title: For Sale:  Colt riffle
postcontent:
In the predawn hours of April 17, 1961, the Deputy Director of the CIA placed a phone call to President John F. Kennedy urgently requesting promised air support for the Bay of Pigs invasion that been launched only hours before. The invasion force of Cuban expatriates had immediately come under heavy fire from Castro's waiting troops and were pinned down on the beach head. Kennedy refused the request for air support and that meant certain defeat for the 1,400 Cubans of "Brigade 2506" and the CIA backed overthrow of Fidel Castro. Shorty after the failed invasion, Kennedy fired the Director of the CIA, Allen Dulles and his Deputy Director, General Charles P. Cabell. General Cabell never forgave Kennedy for this betrayal and bitterly criticized him publicly, often describing Kennedy as a traitor. 

The man that made that fateful 4 am phone call to John Kennedy was the owner of the Winchester carbine offered in this listing. General Charles P. Cabell served as Deputy Director CIA from 1958 to 1962 when he was fired by JFK. He later gave the carbine to his brother, Earle Cabell who was the Mayor of Dallas, Texas when Kennedy visited that city - and was assassinated on November 22, 1963. 

This fine Winchester saddle ring carbine was made in 1920. It is in 30 wcf caliber and overall condition is 90%. The Lyman 56 receiver sight was installed at the Winchester factory according to the letter of provenance that accompanies the carbine. This letter is on Cabell family letterhead and the serial number of this carbine is listed. The letter will be provided to the buyer of this Winchester. 

This is a rare opportunity to own a piece of history that was owned by two prominent men during our nation's turbulent Cold War era. The failed Bay of Pigs invasion led directly to the Cuban Missile Crisis of 1962 - we'd never been closer to all out nuclear war! 

I will provide any additional photos you would like to see, just specify the specific views you want, and I will try to answer any questions you may have regarding this Winchester. 

Photo 9: L to R, Allen Dulles, Ed Lansdale, Charles Cabell, Nathan Twining Photo 10: Gen. Charles P. Cabell, Deputy Director CIA Photo 11: Mayor and Mrs. Earle Cabell greeting JFK and Jackie at Love Field, Nov. 22. 1963. Photo 12: Arlington National Cemetery

title: For Sale:  1877 Colt Lightening DA .38 Reduced Price!
postcontent: On consignment. Refinished at some earlier date???, fully functioning, Colt's first double action revolver. One beautiful revolver with 95% of finish remaining, although some of the bluing on the barrel is a little faded and the case hardened receiver has a few commonly found wear areas. The front sight has been lowered to enable it clear the holster quickly and/or make it a more accurate shooter. Attractive case hardening on the receiver with blued cylinder, barrel, hammer, trigger guard and trigger. This revolver, serial number 96543, was manufactured in 1894, now a spry 120 years old. Has a tight lock up and functions very well, especially considering the internal workings on this model were infamously its weak point. Blue Book values? Not knowing if it was refinished or not, but the fact that front sight was modified (would love to know by whom - a gunslinger?, an outlaw?, a Sheriff?) the starting bid for this fine revolver is for a Colt 1877 evaluated at between 60 and 70% for its fine action and good looks. This revolver will fit fine in any gun collector's case and where some collectors see the short sight as a flaw and degrading feature, to me it's a mystery. Did someone need it to be quick on the draw or some other reason? Let your research and treasure hunt begin.
